  "description": "About 90 of the most basic kanji, the level expected for JLPT N5. Each kanji is tested both ways — recall the meaning from the character and the character from the meaning — tracked separately. Readings are simplified to one main reading.",
  "primerTitle": "Kanji at N5 — how to read this deck",
  "primer": "**Kanji** are the logographic characters borrowed from Chinese; each one carries a *meaning* and one or more *readings*. This is a **recall deck of ~103 of the most basic kanji** — the set expected at **JLPT N5**, the easiest level of the Japanese proficiency exam. They are grouped by theme (numbers, time, nature, body, common verbs, places, adjectives, …). Because there are ~103, this primer **orients** you rather than listing them all — it explains the structure and gives a high-frequency starter set; the deck itself drills the full list.\n\n### Two kinds of reading\nMost kanji have two reading families, and the cards show both (the **say** field gives the main one):\n- **on'yomi** — the *Sino-Japanese* reading, derived from Chinese. Used mostly in **compounds** of two or more kanji (e.g. 学校 *gakkō* 'school' uses the *on* readings *gaku* + *kō*). On readings are conventionally written in katakana in dictionaries.\n- **kun'yomi** — the *native Japanese* reading, used when the kanji stands **alone** or with hiragana okurigana (e.g. 山 alone = *yama* 'mountain'; 見る *miru* 'to see', where 見 takes the kun reading *mi* and る is okurigana).\n\nA card like 月 — *month / moon — getsu, tsuki* lists the **meaning** plus *getsu* (on) and *tsuki* (kun). Verbs are shown with the okurigana in parentheses, e.g. 行 *kō, i(ku)* — the *i* is the kanji's part, *ku* is the trailing hiragana.\n\n### Card structure\nEach kanji is tested **both directions**, tracked separately:\n- character → meaning + reading (\"what is 水?\" → water / *sui, mizu*)\n- meaning → character (\"write 'water'\" → 水)\n\n### A recall method\n1. **Anchor on meaning first**, then attach the readings — pick the *on* for compounds, the *kun* for standalone use.\n2. Use **pictographs** where you can: 山 looks like a mountain, 川 like a flowing river, 木 like a tree, 田 like a divided rice field.\n3. Spot **components**: 休 is 人 (person) beside 木 (tree) = rest; 好 is 女 (woman) + 子 (child) = to like. Reusing known pieces is the fastest path through the set.\n4. Lean on **high-frequency compounds** to fix readings: 日本 *Nihon* (Japan), 学生 *gakusei* (student), 電車 *densha* (train).\n\n### High-frequency starter set (~18 of the ~103)\n| Kanji | Meaning | Reading |\n|---|---|---|\n| 一 | one | ichi |\n| 二 | two | ni |\n| 三 | three | san |\n| 日 | day / sun | nichi, hi |\n| 月 | month / moon | getsu, tsuki |\n| 人 | person | jin, hito |\n| 大 | big | dai, ō(kii) |\n| 小 | small | shō, chii(sai) |\n| 中 | middle / inside | chū, naka |\n| 山 | mountain | san, yama |\n| 川 | river | sen, kawa |\n| 水 | water | sui, mizu |\n| 火 | fire | ka, hi |\n| 木 | tree / wood | moku, ki |\n| 本 | book / origin | hon, moto |\n| 行 | to go | kō, i(ku) |\n| 見 | to see | ken, mi(ru) |\n| 学 | study | gaku, mana(bu) |\n\nThese recur constantly; master them first, then the rest of the deck follows the same meaning + on/kun pattern. The remaining ~85 kanji are drilled by the cards, not enumerated here.",
